                    <div class="MessageList Discussion"><!-- Page Title -->
<div id="Item_0" class="PageTitle"><div class="Options"></div><h1>The Battle of Malaya and Singapore</h1></div>

<div id="Discussion_41572" class="Item ItemDiscussion">
    <div class="Discussion">
        <div class="Item-Header DiscussionHeader">
            <div class="AuthorWrap">
            <span class="Author">
                <a title="SSgt. Gibson" href="https://vanilla.29th.org/profile/SSgt.%20Gibson" class="PhotoWrap"><img src="../../uploads/userpics/115/nQPS06R9FYUTM.jpg" alt="SSgt. Gibson" class="ProfilePhoto ProfilePhotoMedium" /></a><a href="https://vanilla.29th.org/profile/SSgt.%20Gibson" class="Username">SSgt. Gibson</a>            </span>
            <span class="AuthorInfo">
                            </span>
            </div>
            <div class="Meta DiscussionMeta">
            <span class="MItem DateCreated">
                <a href="the-battle-of-malaya-and-singapore" class="Permalink" rel="nofollow"><time title="November 4, 2020 3:45AM" datetime="2020-11-04T03:45:36+00:00">November 2020</time></a>            </span>
                                 <span class="MItem Category"> in <a href="../../categories/civil-announcements">Civil Announcements</a></span>             </div>
        </div>
                <div class="Item-BodyWrap">
            <div class="Item-Body">
                <div class="Message userContent">
                    <p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: x-large; font-family: Verdana;"><u><b>THE BATTLE OF MALAYA AND SINGAPORE</b></u></span></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;"><b>8 DEC 1941 – 15 FEB 1942</b></span></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Esz2xjy.jpg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Japanese troops clearing streets, Kuala Lumpur, January 1942.</div>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">My home country, Singapore, was the site of one of the most significant events in the Pacific War. Before World War Two, Singapore was considered the gem of the British Empire, a “Gibraltar of the East”, and an “impregnable fortress”. On 15 February 1942, these ideas were shattered as myths. A total of 120,000 British and Allied troops were defeated by and surrendered to the Imperial Japanese Army (IJA) which numbered only 70,000. In just three months, the IJA forces swept the entire Malayan peninsula of 700 miles, inflicted decisive defeats on the Allied troops in key battles, and captured Singapore. Prime Minister Winston Churchill reacted to this defeat in anguish, describing it as the “worst disaster” in British military history. His close companions noted that the tragic loss of Singapore in 1942 remained in Churchill’s memory for years to come.<br />
<br /></span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Background</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">How did this “disaster” happen for the British forces? Before we answer this question, we must first establish the world’s geopolitical situation at the winter of 1941. As the Axis forces in Europe were making huge gains in the Soviet Union, Britain was already at war for two years and in a precarious predicament. It only miraculously avoided disaster at the events of Dunkirk and the Battle of Britain in 1940. Naturally, Home Command was prioritizing Europe and Africa. By December 1941, Southeast Asia had become an increasingly important strategic location for the Japanese; British colonies and dominions in Asia seemed vulnerable due to the changing world situation. Unlike France which capitulated and gave Indochina to the Japanese, in 1941, Britain still owned the colonies in the East – Malaya, Burma, India, and the Gibraltar of the East: Singapore.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Meanwhile, the Japanese in 1941 were bogged down in the war with China since 1937. After taking the vital coastal cities and North China, the Japanese assault could push no further inland, with cumulative casualties. Japan, facing an embargo from the United States and others, needed oil desperately and could only gather it from the Dutch East Indies (today Indonesia), which was still controlled by the Netherlands despite having capitulated. However, weakened British, Dutch and French empires formed opportunities in Southeast Asia.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Malaya and Singapore were strategically important to the Japanese for three reasons. First, Malaya owned half of the world’s rubber plantations and tin mines. Second, the region had a large population of ethnic Chinese people who also formed the majority in Singapore. They were highly supportive of the Kuomintang and contributed significant relief effort to China, additionally boycotting Japanese goods. Capturing the assets of rich overseas Chinese in the region would be beneficial to the Japanese. Third, the geographic location of Singapore, as well as its fortifications, meant possession of it would hold the Straits of Malacca as a springboard to attack the East Indies and defend against British counter attacks from India. Meanwhile, it also meant that the so-called impregnable fortress would be in Japan’s hands, a great boost to the weary civilian population which had seen the country at war since 1937. From a Japanese strategic point of view, Malaya, Singapore, and eventually all of the East Indies were vital lands needed to be taken if the Japanese were to one day win in China.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">At the same time, the United States also controlled the Philippines, a large blob in the way of the rich resources of the East Indies. The Japanese military’s perspective was that it was cornered, needing to find a way to solve her suffocating resource and strategic problem, lest it face utter defeat in China and potential loss of its empire. The opportune time came when most of the U.S Pacific Fleet was reported to be docked in Pearl Harbor.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/3nZmlGF.jpeg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Overall Japanese Pacific plan</div>

<p><br /></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Order of Battle</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/cUmdy10.jpeg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Malaya invasion plan</div>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Unlike popular belief, the Japanese attack on the Pacific was not due to crazed radical militaristic ambition, but was treated as a necessary action for survival. It was a carefully calculated “do or die” step which Imperial Japan had planned for several years. General Headquarters of the Imperial Japanese Army (IJA) made the decision to perform an all-out strike and defeat all opponents in one decisive and planned strike; the U.S Navy would be crippled, out of the way, by losing capital ships in Hawaii. Meanwhile, the Japanese Army would invade key British, Dutch and American-held naval bases and port cities, proceeding onwards to take the rest of the Asian colonies. The “Southern Expeditionary Group” (Nanpogun) was set up with over 1 million personnel for objectives in Southeast Asia. Prior to this, Japanese intelligence had already been active in Malaya and spent years studying the ground. The Japanese set up contacts with local Malays and Indians, whom they attempted to align, foster anti-British sentiments, and, most importantly, gather military information and maps. On 7 December 1941 (8 December in Tokyo), the plan was commenced.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Assigned to invade Malaya and Singapore was the IJA “25th Army”, a total of 70,000 crack troops commanded by General Yamashita Tomoyuki. This included 3 full strength divisions with experience in China, including the elite Imperial Guards Division. Supplementing this was tank regiments which had a total of 400 vehicles, including the Type 95 Ha-Go and Type 97 Chi-ha tanks. The first transports were sent across the sea at night from Saigon and landed on the Northern Malay coast on the morning of 8 December.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/ioyaiFK.jpg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Japanese uniform used in 1941, Malaya</div>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">The opponents on the Malay Peninsula was the British “Malaya Command” led by General Arthur Percival. This included two Indian divisions, the Australian 8th Division, as well as the 18th British Division, and volunteers from local ethnic Chinese and Malay population: a total force of 120,000 men. Prior to the battle, the British had called about half of these reinforcements only a few months before. Upon news of the Japanese landing at Thailand, more British troops, including the 18th Infantry Division, were rushed to Singapore. However, the British did not possess tanks other than Bren carriers, as the jungles were deemed unsuitable for tanks.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Ybwb7Qg.jpg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">British uniform worn in 1941, Malaya</div>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">A significant part of the Japanese plan was to overwhelm the British Air force and Navy. The Japanese had slightly superior aircraft but only used them sparingly in the campaign due to AA defences. Thus, the first step taken on 8 December was also to cripple any resistance from the air which might slow down an invasion. In one day, only 50 out of the 110 Allied aircraft were destroyed in air strikes. The remainder only consisted of old Brewster and Buffalo aircraft and a few Hurricanes.</span></p>

<p><br /></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Sinking of the HMS Prince of Wales and Repulse</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Japanese planners knew that the Royal Navy used Singapore as a giant naval base for its power projection in Asia. Since Japan’s navy was mostly deployed in the Pacific, Japanese forces only had one cruiser and some destroyers to escort the convoys, relying on air power to secure the seas.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">A key event which spelled the fate of the battle was the sinking of 2 British battleships, which was the bulk of the British Navy in the far east. Upon hearing news of Japanese landings, this was designated Force Z and sent to intercept Japanese troop ships. Unfortunately for the British, there was no air support available, but the risky decision to send them under the guise of poor weather was still made. On December 10th, the troops were spotted by Japanese submarines in the area. Without any form of air cover, the battleships were quickly destroyed by G4M torpedo bombers.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/JzEX2Vn.jpeg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Japanese pilot’s depiction of the event</div>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/fNHqAzg.jpeg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Torpedo Bomber Mitsubishi G4M1 “Betty”, referred by Japanese as Hamaki/葉巻(Cigar)</div>

<p><br /></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Malaya</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Before the real battles had even started, the British already lost any real chance of air-naval superiority due to a sudden Japanese strike. On the 8th of December, when Japanese troops landed on the beaches of Kota Bharu in Kelantan, northern Malaya, they were met by some Allied ground troops. Although the defenders managed to destroy two Japanese transport ships and bring down the first wave of troops, the overwhelming numbers of Japanese troops forced the Allies to retreat.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/DOwprYs.jpg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Japanese troops cross a river in Malaya</div>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">The British had anticipated a Japanese landward attack and developed a first-strike plan known as Operation Matador. Under the plan, Allied forces would intercept the Japanese forces just over the Thai border, giving the main forces in Malaya time to gather and attack. However, the Allies failed to detect the Japanese landings before they happened, and British High Command calculated that the defenses at the beach would be sufficient. As the beach fell, the Allied troops, as per the plan, were ordered to Jitra, Kedah, to form an inland defense line, an elastic defense plan. The problem was that Japanese troops already crossed the Thai border and entered northwest Malaya with little resistance. The Japanese, having acquired the port of Kota Bahru, was able to acquire bicycles and additional supplies to move quickly down the peninsula and could use ports to disembark most of their main force and tanks from Saigon.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/BKDWMLj.jpeg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Japanese troops in Kuala Lumpur, January 1942</div>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">The defensive line at Jitra was reached by the Japanese on December 13th, only less than a week after the initial landing. This line was difficult to defend due to it crossing a mountain and very close to the Thai border. Allied forces retreated again inland in the Peninisula to the midpoint of Malaya at the Slim River. The Battle of Slim River on January 7th, 1942 was a disaster for the Allies. Of the 5,000 men from the two Indian brigades who had fought in the battle, only 25% survived. Losing Slim River also resulted in the loss of central Malaya to the Japanese, and Allied troops were quickly encircled and overwhelmed. By the end of January, important Malayan cities Penang and Kuala Lumpur were lost. This meant the Allies had to retreat to Johore and set up a defensive line there, the last before Singapore. At Muar, Johore, 4,000 Allied infantry managed to delay the Japanese advance. A major problem was that most of the allied troops were recruits from India and Malayan volunteers, unlike the more well-trained British and Australian troops. At Muar, there was a casualty rate on the Allies at around 70-75%.</span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/kQuU825.jpg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Australian 8th Division anti-tank guns destroyed nine tanks in Johor, slowing the Japanese advance by a few days</div>

<p><br /></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Singapore<br />
<span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Trying to slow the overwhelmingly rapid Japanese advance, the British blew up the causeway linking Malaysia to Singapore on February 8th. The Japanese simply used the fishing boats and rafts from villages in Malaya to cross at night. Australian troops fought off initial landing attempts while inflicting casualties on the Japanese. However, the Australian troops retreated unnecessarily amidst some confusion of battle, allowing the Japanese to gain a strong foothold at the shore defense installations. Subsequent landings by the Japanese were unopposed. The military situation for the British under Percival worsened. With shortage of food and especially water, along with highly demoralized troops, Percival surrendered his army unconditionally on February 15th.</span></span></p>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Ln50RTv.jpeg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">British surrender in Singapore</div>

<p></p><div style="text-align: center;"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/0Tj0G7p.jpg" alt="Image description" /></div><br />
<div style="text-align: center;">Overall course of events in Malayan Campaign</div>

<p><br /></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Concluding Thoughts<br />
<span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">The British lost this battle disastrously due to three broad reasons. They suffered from lack of counter-intelligence/preparation, lack of air superiority, and mostly, the Japanese advantage of deploying the first strike. Compounding these three reasons was overconfidence of the High Command and making the assumption that tanks could not be used in jungles. Additionally, because they had strong ground intelligence, the Japanese knew British weak points which allowed a decisive first strike. Once the first strike was successfully done, morale was crippled among the confused defending forces, while morale soared among attacking forces.</span></span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">It is also likely that the British simply did not have enough air equipment or reliable manpower in the Far East due to overextension; priority was placed on the Home Isles and the intense battle ongoing in North Africa. In Commonwealth countries, it is often remembered that of these 120,000 troops, many were sent to the railways of Burma as workers in near-death or deathly conditions. The gruesome details can be found elsewhere.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">As a historian writing this in October 2020, I am without doubt that this campaign has affected this region and the world dramatically. Singapore as an English-speaking former colony often uses this story to explain its contemporary Israel-like defense policy, painting a picture of vulnerability using this battle, and justifying conscription of 2 years which I have served. This Israeli-Singapore model is useful for the defense policies and strategies of other small states.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Timeline</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">7–8 Dec 1941: Japanese attack Pearl Harbor; Japanese troops land in Northern Malaya.<br />
10 Dec 1941: Japanese sink HMS Repulse and Prince of Wales.<br />
19 Dec 1941: Japanese capture Penang.<br />
7 Jan 1942: Battle of Slim River.<br />
11 Jan 1942: Japanese capture Kuala Lumpur.<br />
31 Jan 1942: Last Allied troops cross the Causeway into Singapore.<br />
15 Feb 1942: Fall of Singapore.</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size: large; font-family: Verdana;">Casualties<br />
<span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Verdana;">Allied Casualties<br />
7,531 killed <br />
10,000 wounded<br />
130,000 captured<br />
Japanese Casualties<br />
3,507 killed<br />
6,150 wounded</span></span></p>

<hr />

<p><span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Helvetica;"><em>Written by</em> PFC Tan<br />
<span style="font-size: medium; font-family: Helvetica;"><em>Edited by</em> Sgt. Gibson &amp; Cpl. J. Lee</span></span></p>
                </div>
